    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-02-19T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-02-19T17:00:00-05:00" n="110"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d110">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.3731/522: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-19T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 19, 1934—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 5:52 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>166. My telegram No. 161, February 17, 3 p.m. I have just had a further
                    discussion on the commercial treaty revision with the Secretaries <pb
                        facs="0178" n="112" xml:id="pg_112"/> of State, Treasury, and Agriculture,
                    and negotiations between the technical advisers will be commenced immediately
                    and continue constantly. The Cuban technical advisers are Pedro Arango of the
                    Department of Agriculture and Commerce, Roberto Netto of the Treasury, and Angel
                    Solano of State Department.<note n="22" xml:id="d110fn22">The American technical
                        advisers were Albert F. Nufer, Commercial Attaché at Habana; Walter J.
                        Donnelly, appointed Commercial Attaché at Habana, January 9, 1934; and Harry
                        R. Turkel, of the Treaty Division, Department of State, assigned to the
                        Embassy in Cuba, February-August, 1934.</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
